'''Ingrid Bergman'''{{efn|{{IPA-sv|Àà…™Ãå≈ãÀêr…™d Ààb√¶Ãårjman|lang|Sv-Ingrid_Bergman_2.ogg}}}} (29 August 1915{{spnd}}29 August 1982) was a Swedish actress who starred in a variety of European and American films, television movies, and plays.<ref name="WVobit">Obituary ''[[Variety Obituaries|Variety]]'', 1 September 1982.</ref> With a career spanning five decades,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Biography - The Official Licensing Website of Ingrid Bergman|url=https://www.ingridbergman.com/biography/|access-date=12 November 2020|website=Ingrid Bergman|archive-date=30 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530175445/http://www.ingridbergman.com/about/bio.htm|url-status=dead}}</ref> she is often regarded as one of the most influential screen figures in cinematic history.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Harlan|first=Justin|date=12 April 2018|title=Criterion Honors the Great "Betterlater" with Eclipse Series 46: Ingrid Bergman's Swedish Years|url=https://cinapse.co/criterion-honors-the-great-betterlater-with-eclipse-series-46-ingrid-bergmans-swedish-years-81e2ffbf323|access-date=12 November 2020|website=Medium}}</ref> 

According to the ''[[St. James Encyclopedia of Popular Culture]]'', upon her arrival in the U.S. Bergman quickly became "the ideal of American womanhood" and a contender for Hollywood's greatest leading actress.<ref name=James>{{cite book|first1=Tom|last1=Pendergast|first2=Sara|last2=Pendergast|title=St. James Encyclopedia of Popular Culture|publisher=[[Gale Publishing]]|location=Farmington Hills, Michigan|date=2000|isbn=1-55862-405-8|title-link=St. James Encyclopedia of Popular Culture}}</ref> [[David O. Selznick]] once called her "the most completely conscientious actress" he had ever worked with. In 1999, the [[American Film Institute]] recognised Bergman as the fourth greatest female [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Stars|screen legend]] of [[Classical Hollywood cinema|Classic Hollywood Cinema]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afi.com/tvevents/100years/stars.aspx|title=AFI's 100 Years ... 100 Stars|publisher=[[American Film Institute]]|access-date=23 October 2006|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061020084914/http://www.afi.com/tvevents/100years/stars.aspx|archive-date=20 October 2006}}</ref>

She won [[List of awards and nominations received by Ingrid Bergman|numerous accolades]], including three [[Academy Awards]], two [[Primetime Emmy Awards]], a [[Tony Award]], four [[Golden Globe Awards]], [[BAFTA Award]] and a [[Volpi Cup for Best Actress|Volpi Cup]]. She is one of only four actresses to have received at least [[List of actors with two or more Academy Awards in acting categories|three acting Academy Awards]] (only [[Katharine Hepburn]] has four).

Born in [[Stockholm]] to a Swedish father and a German mother, Bergman began her acting career in Swedish and German films. Her introduction to the U.S. audience came in the English-language remake of ''[[Intermezzo (1939 film)|Intermezzo]]'' (1939). Known for her naturally luminous beauty, she starred in ''[[Casablanca (film)|Casablanca]]'' (1942) as Ilsa Lund, her most famous role, opposite [[Humphrey Bogart]]. Bergman's notable performances in the 1940s include the dramas ''[[For Whom the Bell Tolls (film)|For Whom the Bell Tolls]]'' (1943), ''[[Gaslight (1944 film)|Gaslight]]'' (1944), ''[[The Bells of St. Mary's]]'' (1945), and ''[[Joan of Arc (1948 film)|Joan of Arc]]'' (1948), all of which earned her nominations for the [[Academy Award for Best Actress]]; she won for ''Gaslight''. She made three films with [[Alfred Hitchcock]]: ''[[Spellbound (1945 film)|Spellbound]]'' (1945), with [[Gregory Peck]], [[Notorious (1946 film)|''Notorious'']] (1946), opposite [[Cary Grant]] and ''[[Under Capricorn]]'' (1949), alongside [[Joseph Cotten]].

In 1950, she starred in [[Roberto Rossellini]]'s ''[[Stromboli (film)|Stromboli]]'', released after the revelation she was having an affair with Rossellini; that and her pregnancy prior to their marriage created a scandal in the U.S. that prompted her to remain in Europe for several years. During this time she starred in Rossellini's [[Europe '51|''Europa '51'']] and ''[[Journey to Italy]]'' (1954), now critically acclaimed, the former of which won her the [[Volpi Cup for Best Actress]]. She had a successful return to working for a Hollywood studio in ''[[Anastasia (1956 film)|Anastasia]]'' (1956), winning her second Academy Award for Best Actress. Soon after, she co-starred with Grant in the romance ''[[Indiscreet (1958 film)|Indiscreet]]'' (1958). In 1969, she starred in the acclaimed and highly successful film ''[[Cactus Flower (film)|Cactus Flower]]''. In later years, Bergman won her third Academy Award, this one for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]], for her role in ''[[Murder on the Orient Express (1974 film)|Murder on the Orient Express]]'' (1974). In 1978, she starred in [[Ingmar Bergman]]'s (no relation) Swedish ''[[Autumn Sonata]]'' receiving her sixth Best Actress nomination. Bergman spoke five languages ‚Äì Swedish, English, German, Italian and French ‚Äì and acted in each.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://inews.co.uk/culture/film/isabella-rossellini-extraordinary-gifts-mother-ingrid-bergman-16783|title=Isabella Rossellini: my mother Ingrid Bergman taught me independence|last=Rossellini|first=Isabella|date=4 August 2016|website=[[i (newspaper)|i]]|access-date=22 September 2021}}</ref>

In her final role, she portrayed the late Israeli Prime Minister [[Golda Meir]] in the television miniseries ''[[A Woman Called Golda]]'' (1982) for which she posthumously won her second [[Emmy Award]] for Best Actress. In 1974, Bergman discovered she was suffering from breast cancer but continued to work until shortly before her death on her sixty-seventh birthday.

