Ingrid Bergman was born on 29 August 1915 in Stockholm, to a Swedish father, Justus Samuel Bergman (2 May 1871 ‚Äì 29 July 1929),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ingridbergman.com/about/bio.htm|title=The Official Ingrid Bergman Web Site|website=Ingridbergman.com|access-date=31 May 2017|archive-date=30 May 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170530175445/http://www.ingridbergman.com/about/bio.htm|url-status=dead}}</ref> and his [[German people|German]] wife, Frieda "Friedel" Henriette Auguste Louise ([[n√©e]] Adler) Bergman (12 September 1884 ‚Äì 19 January 1918), who was born in [[Kiel]].<ref name=Chandler>{{cite book|author=Chandler, Charlotte|title=Ingrid: Ingrid Bergman, A Personal Biography|publisher=Simon & Schuster|year=2007|location=New York|isbn=978-0-7432-9421-8|pages=[https://archive.org/details/ingridingridberg00chan/page/19 19, 21, 294]|url=https://archive.org/details/ingridingridberg00chan/page/19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uZuwAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA13|title=Ingrid Bergman and her American Relatives|isbn=9780761861515|last1=Ziolkowska-Boehm|first1=Aleksandra|date=28 August 2013}}</ref> Her parents married in [[Hamburg]] on 13 June 1907.<ref name="auto2">{{Cite web|url=https://ancestrylibrary.proquest.com/aleweb/ale/do/login|title=Ancestry Library Edition|website=ancestrylibrary.proquest.com}}</ref><ref>''Standesamt Hamburg'' 3, 1907 No. 173.</ref> She was named after [[Ingrid of Sweden|Princess Ingrid of Sweden]]. Although she was raised in Sweden, she spent her summers in Germany and spoke fluent German.<ref>{{cite book |first=Arne |last=Lunde |title=Nordic Exposures: Scandinavian Identities in Classical Hollywood Cinema |page=157 |publisher=University of Washington Press |year=2011 |isbn=9780295800844}}</ref>

Bergman was raised an only child, as two older siblings had died in infancy before she was born. When she was
two and a half years old, her mother died. Justus Bergman had wanted his daughter to become an opera star and had her take voice lessons for three years.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Russell Taylor|first=John|url=https://archive.org/details/ingridbergman00tayl|title=Ingrid Bergman|publisher=St. Martin's Press|year=1983|isbn=0-312-41796-9|location=Great Britain|url-access=registration}}</ref> He sent her to the [[Palmgrenska samskolan|Palmgrenska Samskolan]], a prestigious girls' school in Stockholm where Bergman was reportedly neither a good student nor popular.<ref name=":0" />

Since Justus was a photographer, he loved to document his daughter's birthdays with his camera.<ref name="LifeMag" /> He made his daughter one of his favorite photographic subjects. She enjoyed dancing, dressing up and acting in front of her father's lenses. "I was perhaps the most photographed child in Scandinavia", quipped Bergman in her later years.<ref name="HutchinsonOpinion" /> In 1929, when Bergman was around 14, her father died of stomach cancer. Losing her parents at such a young age was a trauma that Bergman later described as "living with an ache", an experience she was not even aware of.<ref name="HutchinsonOpinion" />

After her father's death, Bergman was sent to live with her paternal aunt, Ellen, who died of heart disease six months later. Bergman then lived with her maternal aunt Hulda and her husband Otto, who had five children of their own. She also visited her other maternal aunt, Elsa Adler, whom the young girl called ''Mutti'' (Mom) according to family lore.<ref name="Chandler" />{{rp|294}} She later said she "knew from the beginning that [she] wanted to be an actress," sometimes wearing her deceased mother's clothing, and staging plays in her father's empty studio.{{cn|date=August 2022}}

Bergman spoke Swedish and German as [[first language]]s, English and Italian (acquired later, while living in the US and Italy),<ref name="Leamer2" /> and French (learned in school). She acted in each of these languages at various times.<ref name="JP" />

Bergman received a scholarship to the state-sponsored [[Royal Dramatic Theatre School]], where [[Greta Garbo]] had some years earlier earned a similar scholarship. After several months, she was given a part in a new play, ''Ett Brott'' (''A Crime''), written by [[Sigfrid Siwertz]]. This was "totally against procedure" at the school, where girls were expected to complete three years of study before getting such acting roles.<ref name="Chandler" />{{rp|33}} During her first summer break, Bergman was hired by a Swedish film studio, which led her to leave the Royal Dramatic Theatre after just one year to work in films full-time.{{cn|date=August 2022}}

== Career ==
=== 1935‚àí1938: Swedish years ===
Bergman's first film experience was as an [[Extra (acting)|extra]] in the 1932 film ''Landskamp'', an experience she described as "walking on holy ground".<ref name="HutchinsonOpinion" /> Her first speaking role was a small part in ''[[Munkbrogreven]]'' (1934).<ref name="HutchinsonOpinion" /> Bergman played Elsa, a maid in a seedy hotel, being pursued by the leading man, [[Edvin Adolphson]]. Critics called her "hefty and sure of herself", and "somewhat overweight ... with an unusual way of speaking her lines". The unflatteringly striped costume that she wore may have contributed to the unfavorable comments regarding her appearance.<ref name=Eclipse/><ref name="HutchinsonOpinion" /> Soon after, ''Munkbrogreven'', Bergman was offered a studio contract and placed under director [[Gustaf Molander]].<ref name="HutchinsonOpinion"/>
{{Multiple image
